# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thread-network-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group defined encapsulation, header compression, neighbor discovery and other mechanisms that allow IPv6 to operate over IEEE 802.15.4 based networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Although IPv4 and IPv6 protocols do not generally care about the physical and MAC layers they operate over, the low-power devices and small packet size defined by IEEE 802.15.4 make it desirable to adapt to these layers.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The base specification developed by the 6LoWPAN IETF group is RFC 4944 (updated by RFC 6282 with header compression, RFC 6775 with neighbor discovery optimization, RFC 8931 with selective fragment recovery and with smaller changes in RFC 8025 and RFC 8066).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The problem statement document is RFC 4919.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 over Bluetooth Low Energy using 6LoWPAN techniques is described in RFC 7668.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The targets for IPv6 networking for low-power radio communication are devices that need wireless connectivity to many other devices at lower data rates for devices with very limited power consumption.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The header compression mechanisms in RFC 6282 are used to allow IPv6 packets to travel over such networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 is also in use on the smart grid enabling smart meters and other devices to build a micro mesh network before sending the data back to the billing system using the IPv6 backbone.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Some of these networks run over IEEE 802.15.4 radios, and therefore use the header compression and fragmentation as specified by RFC6282.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Thread is a standard from a group of more than fifty companies for a protocol running over 6LoWPAN to enable home automation.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The specification is available at no cost as of 24 June 2022, but paid membership is required to implement the protocol.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 2015-10-29.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The protocol most directly competes with Z-Wave and Zigbee IP.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] In IoT device communications using the Matter standard, Thread is one of two possible wireless transport layers.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] As with all link-layer mappings of IP, RFC4944 provides a number of functions.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Beyond the usual differences between L2 and L3 networks, mapping from the IPv6 network to the IEEE 802.15.4 network poses additional design challenges (see RFC 4919 for an overview).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 requires the link maximum transmission unit (MTU) to be at least 1280 octets.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] In contrast, IEEE 802.15.4's standard frame size is 127 octets.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] A maximum frame overhead of 25 octets and an optional but highly recommended security feature at the link layer poses an additional overhead of up to 21 octets are for AES-CCM-128.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] This leaves only 81 octets for the upper layers.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Since this is so much less than 1280, 6LoWPAN defines a fragmentation and reassembly layer.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Further, the standard IPv6 Header is 40 octets long, so header compression is defined as well.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are assigned 128 bit IP addresses in a hierarchical manner, through an arbitrary length network prefix.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices may use either of IEEE 64 bit extended addresses or, after an association event, 16 bit addresses that are unique within a PAN.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] There is also a PAN-ID for a group of physically collocated IEEE 802.15.4 devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices are intentionally constrained in form factor to reduce costs (allowing for large-scale network of many devices), reduce power consumption (allowing battery powered devices) and allow flexibility of installation (e.g. small devices for body-worn networks).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] On the other hand, wired nodes in the IP domain are not constrained in this way; they can be larger and make use of mains power supplies.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are geared towards attaining high speeds.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Algorithms and protocols implemented at the higher layers such as TCP kernel of the TCP/IP are optimized to handle typical network problems such as congestion.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] In IEEE 802.15.4-compliant devices, energy conservation and code-size optimization remain at the top of the agenda.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] An adaptation mechanism to allow interoperability between IPv6 domain and the IEEE 802.15.4 can best be viewed as a layer problem.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Identifying the functionality of this layer and defining newer packet formats, if needed, is an enticing research area.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] RFC 4944 proposes an adaptation layer to allow the transmission of IPv6 datagrams over IEEE 802.15.4 networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The management of addresses for devices that communicate across the two dissimilar domains of IPv6 and IEEE 802.15.4 is cumbersome, if not exhaustingly complex.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Several routing protocols have been proposed by the 6LoWPAN community such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] However, only two routing protocols are currently legitimate for large-scale deployments: LOADng standardized by the ITU under the recommendation ITU-T G.9903 and RPL standardized by the IETF ROLL working group.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN routing scheme can be carried out in two different ways: *mesh-under* and *route-over*.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Initially, several routing protocols were developed by the 6LoWPAN community, such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW .
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Since IP-enabled devices may require the formation of ad hoc networks, the current state of neighboring devices and the services hosted by such devices will need to be known.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPv6 neighbour discovery extensions is an internet draft proposed as a contribution in this area.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 nodes can operate in either secure mode or non-secure mode.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 defines the IPv6 header compression mechanism for LowPAN: LOWPAN_HC1.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] It also includes compression of the UDP header over 4 bytes, but does not allow compression of the *Checksum*.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Additionally, it restricts the range of UDP ports from 61616 to 61631 in order to compress this value to 4 bits.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] This IPv6 header compression can only be applied to local link addresses.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] To overcome this problem, an IETF LOWPAN_HC1g draft was published.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] LOWPAN_HC1g applies to global addresses for IP multi-hop communications.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] These two compression mechanisms (LOWPAN_HC1 and LOWPAN_HC1g) are complementary.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] It is therefore necessary to implement both.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Today the proposal of the 6LoWPAN group is to use LOWPAN_IPHC.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] IPHC bytes result from compression of the IPv6 header.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] They mainly integrate information from quality of service (DSCP and ECN), next headers, number of hops and compressed source/destination addresses.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The example below shows the increase in payload compared to the original problem (see 1re figure).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] This payload is in the best case 70 to 75 bytes.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Indeed, if we add the fragmentation information as indicated in the paragraph above, it will decrease to 65-70 bytes for this scenario.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Technological developments in the 1990s (miniaturization of electronics, deployment of new wireless networks and embedded systems) enabled the emergence of new applications for sensor and actuator networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] With the advent of wireless technologies, the first solutions used were completely proprietary (for example Z-Wave or EnOcean).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] With the standard IEEE 802.15.4 (radio use of wireless sensors) new proprietary standards have appeared (for example, ZigBee, WirelessHART **(in)**, etc.).
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] When first thinking about wireless sensor networking, 6LoWPAN was born from a simple idea: why reinvent a protocol when we already have IP?
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Geoff Mulligan proposes the use of IP on 802.15.4 for sensor type equipment.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] , "robust header compression") of IETF were interested.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS released on the implementation of "Arch Rock Company: Primer Pack/IP".
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS is available on the implementation of "Sensinode Company: NanoStack v0.9.4".
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group publishes the RFC 4919 to ensure the interoperability of the network layer.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 sees the light of day, based on the RFC4919.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] This should allow direct connectivity to the Internet of LoWPAN equipment via IPv6 and replace them communication protocols owners like ZigBee,, which was developed after the end of the Smart Dust project.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] The IETF launches the ROLL Working Group.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] , "IP for Smart Objects"), chaired by Geoff Mulligan, is created to promote the use of IP in smart objects.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Smart objects are small type objects switch, detector more commonly called sensors.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] To develop smart grids, President Obama announces an investment of $3.4 billion.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Study demonstrates significant economic prospects in IoT.
[src:thread-network-deep/6lowpan] Cisco buys the company Arch Rock (one of the leaders in BAC applications for WSN), which strengthens the strategic alliance previously signed between Cisco and Itron (metering specialist smart grid),.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is an application-layer protocol that is intended for use in resource-constrained Internet devices, such as wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is designed to easily translate to HTTP for simplified integration with the web, while also meeting specialized requirements such as multicast support, very low overhead, and simplicity.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Multicast, low overhead, and simplicity are important for Internet of things (IoT) and machine-to-machine (M2M) communication, which tend to be embedded and have much less memory and power supply than traditional Internet devices have.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Therefore, efficiency is very important.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP can run on most devices that support UDP or a UDP analogue.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) Constrained RESTful Environments Working Group (CoRE) has done the major standardization work for this protocol.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] In order to make the protocol suitable to IoT and M2M applications, various new functions have been added.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The core of the protocol is specified in RFC 7252.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP makes use of two message types, requests and responses, using a simple, binary header format.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is by default bound to UDP and optionally to DTLS, providing a high level of communications security.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] When bound to UDP, the entire message *must* fit within a single datagram.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] When used with 6LoWPAN as defined in RFC 4944, messages *should* fit into a single IEEE 802.15.4 frame to minimize fragmentation.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The smallest CoAP message is 4 bytes in length, if the token, options and payload fields are omitted, i.e. if it only consists of the CoAP header.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The header is followed by the token value (0 to 8 bytes) which may be followed by a list of options in an optimized type–length–value format.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Any bytes after the header, token and options (if any) are considered the message payload, which is prefixed by the one-byte "payload marker" (0xFF).
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The length of the payload is implied by the datagram length.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The first 4 bytes are mandatory in all CoAP datagrams, they constitute the fixed-size header.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] This describes the datagram's message type for the two message type context of Request and Response.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Indicates the length of the variable-length Token field, which may be 0–8 bytes in length.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The three most significant bits form a number known as the "class", which is analogous to the class of HTTP status codes.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The five least significant bits form a code that communicates further detail about the request or response.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The entire code is typically communicated in the form `class.code` .
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Used to detect message duplication and to match messages of type acknowledgement/reset to messages of type confirmable/non-confirmable.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Every request carries a token (but it may be zero length) whose value was generated by the client.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The server must echo every token value without any modification back to the client in the corresponding response.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] It is intended for use as a client-local identifier to match requests and responses, especially for concurrent requests.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Matching requests and responses is not done with the message ID because a response may be sent in a different message than the acknowledgement (which uses the message ID for matching).
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] For example, this could be done to prevent retransmissions if obtaining the result takes some time.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Such a detached response is called "separate response".
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] In contrast, transmitting the response directly in the acknowledgement is called "piggybacked response" which is expected to be preferred for efficiency reasons.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] There exist proxy implementations which provide forward or reverse proxy functionality for the CoAP protocol and also implementations which translate between protocols like HTTP and CoAP.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] In many CoAP application domains it is essential to have the ability to address several CoAP resources as a group, instead of addressing each resource individually (e.g. to turn on all the CoAP-enabled lights in a room with a single CoAP request triggered by toggling the light switch).
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] To address this need, the IETF has developed an optional extension for CoAP in the form of an experimental RFC: Group Communication for CoAP - RFC 7390 This extension relies on IP multicast to deliver the CoAP request to all group members.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] The use of multicast has certain benefits such as reducing the number of packets needed to deliver the request to the members.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] However, multicast also has its limitations such as poor reliability and being cache-unfriendly.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] An alternative method for CoAP group communication that uses unicasts instead of multicasts relies on having an intermediary where the groups are created.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Clients send their group requests to the intermediary, which in turn sends individual unicast requests to the group members, collects the replies from them, and sends back an aggregated reply to the client.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Research has been conducted on optimizing DTLS by implementing security associates as CoAP resources rather than using DTLS as a security wrapper for CoAP traffic.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] This research has indicated that improvements of up to 6.5 times none optimized implementations.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] In addition to DTLS, RFC8613 defines the Object Security for Constrained RESTful Environments (OSCORE) protocol which provides security for CoAP at the application layer.
[src:thread-network-deep/constrained-application-protocol] Although the protocol standard includes provisions for mitigating the threat of DDoS amplification attacks, these provisions are not implemented in practice, resulting in the presence of over 580,000 targets primarily located in China and attacks up to 320 Gbit/s.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:thread-network-deep/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE standard 802.15.4 is intended to offer the fundamental lower network layers of a type of wireless personal area network (WPAN), which focuses on low-cost, low-speed ubiquitous communication between devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It can be contrasted with other approaches, such as Wi-Fi, which offers more bandwidth and requires more power.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The emphasis is on very low-cost communication of nearby devices with little to no underlying infrastructure, intending to exploit this to lower power consumption even more.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The basic framework conceives a 10-meter communications range with line of sight at a transfer rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Bandwidth tradeoffs are possible to favor more radically embedded devices with even lower power requirements for increased battery operating time, through the definition of not one, but several physical layers.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Lower transfer rates of 20 and 40 kbit/s were initially defined, with the 100 kbit/s rate being added in the current revision.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Even lower rates can be used, which results in lower power consumption.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] As already mentioned, the main goal of IEEE 802.15.4 regarding WPANs is the emphasis on achieving low manufacturing and operating costs through the use of relatively simple transceivers, while enabling application flexibility and adaptability.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Integrated support for secure communications.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Power management functions to adjust compromises of link speed and quality and energy detection.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Support for time- and data-rate–sensitive applications through the ability to operate with either CSMA/CA or TDMA access modes.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The TDMA mode of operation is supported via the GTS feature of the standard.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4-conformant devices may use one of three possible frequency bands for operation (868/915/2450 MHz).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Devices are designed to interact with each other over a conceptually simple wireless network.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The definition of the network layers is based on the OSI model; although only the lower layers are defined in the standard, interaction with upper layers is intended, possibly using an IEEE 802.2 logical link control sublayer accessing the MAC through a convergence sublayer.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Implementations may rely on external devices or be purely embedded, self-functioning devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The *physical layer* (PHY) provides the data transmission service.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It also, provides an interface to the *physical layer management entity*, which offers access to every physical layer management function and maintains a database of information on related personal area networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Thus, the PHY manages the physical radio transceiver, performs channel selection along with energy and signal management functions.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] An optional alternative 868/915 MHz layer is defined using a combination of binary keying and amplitude-shift keying (thus based on parallel, not sequential, spread spectrum; PSSS).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Dynamic switching between supported 868/915 MHz PHYs is possible.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Beyond these three bands, the IEEE 802.15.4c study group considered the newly opened 314–316 MHz, 430–434 MHz, and 779–787 MHz bands in China, while the IEEE 802.15 Task Group 4d defined an amendment to to support the new 950–956 MHz band in Japan.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first standard amendments by these groups were released in April 2009.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4e was chartered to define a MAC amendment to the existing standard 802.15.4-2006 which adopts a channel hopping strategy to improve support for the industrial market.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Channel hopping increases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] On February 6, 2012, the IEEE Standards Association Board approved IEEE 802.15.4e which concluded all Task Group 4e efforts.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The medium access control (MAC) enables the transmission of MAC frames through the use of the physical channel.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Besides the data service, it offers a management interface and itself manages access to the physical channel and network beaconing.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It also controls frame validation, guarantees time slots and handles node associations.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Finally, it offers hook points for secure services.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Note that the IEEE 802.15 standard does *not* use 802.1d or IEEE standard 802.15.4q-2016; i.e., it does not exchange standard Ethernet frames.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The physical frame-format is specified in IEEE standard 802.15.4-2011 in section 5.2.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It is tailored to the fact that most IEEE 802.15.4 PHYs only support frames of up to 127 bytes (adaptation layer protocols such as the IETF's 6LoWPAN provide fragmentation schemes to support larger network layer packets).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] No higher-level layers or interoperability sublayers are defined in the standard.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Other specifications, such as Zigbee, SNAP, and 6LoWPAN/Thread, build on this standard.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] RIOT, OpenWSN, TinyOS, Unison RTOS, DSPnano RTOS, nanoQplus, Contiki and Zephyr operating systems also use some components of IEEE standard 802.15.4-2020 hardware and software.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The standard defines two types of network node.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first one is the **full-function device** (FFD).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It can serve as the coordinator of a personal area network just as it may function as a common node.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It implements a general model of communication which allows it to talk to any other device: it may also relay messages, in which case it is dubbed a coordinator (PAN coordinator when it is in charge of the whole network).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] On the other hand, there are **reduced-function devices** (RFD).
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] These are meant to be extremely simple devices with very modest resource and communication requirements; due to this, they can only communicate with FFDs and can never act as coordinators.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks can be built as either peer-to-peer or star networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] However, every network needs at least one FFD to work as the coordinator of the network.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks are thus formed by groups of devices separated by suitable distances.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Each device has a unique 64-bit identifier, and if some conditions are met, short 16-bit identifiers can be used within a restricted environment.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Namely, within each PAN domain, communications will probably use short identifiers.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] A more structured **star** pattern is also supported, where the coordinator of the network will necessarily be the central node.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Such a network can originate when an FFD decides to create its own PAN and declare itself its coordinator, after choosing a unique PAN identifier.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] After that, other devices can join the network, which is fully independent from all other star networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Frames are the basic unit of data transport, of which there are four fundamental types (data, acknowledgment, beacon and MAC command frames), which provide a reasonable tradeoff between simplicity and robustness.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Additionally, a superframe structure, defined by the coordinator, may be used, in which case two beacons act as its limits and provide synchronization to other devices as well as configuration information.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] A superframe consists of sixteen equal-length slots, which can be further divided into an active part and an inactive part, during which the coordinator may enter power saving mode, not needing to control its network.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Within superframes contention occurs between their limits, and is resolved by CSMA/CA.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Every transmission must end before the arrival of the second beacon.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] As mentioned before, applications with well-defined bandwidth needs can use up to seven domains of one or more contentionless guaranteed time slots, trailing at the end of the superframe.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first part of the superframe must be sufficient to give service to the network structure and its devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Superframes are typically utilized within the context of low-latency devices, whose associations must be kept even if inactive for long periods of time.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers to the coordinator require a beacon synchronization phase, if applicable, followed by CSMA/CA transmission (by means of slots if superframes are in use); acknowledgment is optional.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers from the coordinator usually follow device requests: if beacons are in use, these are used to signal requests; the coordinator acknowledges the request and then sends the data in packets which are acknowledged by the device.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The same is done when superframes are not in use, only in this case there are no beacons to keep track of pending messages.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Point-to-point networks may either use unslotted CSMA/CA or synchronization mechanisms; in this case, communication between any two devices is possible, whereas in "structured" modes one of the devices must be the network coordinator.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] In general, all implemented procedures follow a typical request-confirm/indication-response classification.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The physical medium is accessed through a CSMA/CA access method.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks which are not using beaconing mechanisms utilize an unslotted variation which is based on the listening of the medium, leveraged by a random exponential backoff algorithm; acknowledgments do not adhere to this discipline.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Common data transmission utilizes unallocated slots when beaconing is in use; again, confirmations do not follow the same process.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Confirmation messages may be optional under certain circumstances, in which case a success assumption is made.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Whatever the case, if a device is unable to process a frame at a given time, it simply does not confirm its reception: timeout-based retransmission can be performed a number of times, following after that a decision of whether to abort or keep trying.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Because the predicted environment of these devices demands maximization of battery life, the protocols tend to favor the methods which lead to it, implementing periodic checks for pending messages, the frequency of which depends on application needs.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Regarding secure communications, the MAC sublayer offers facilities which can be harnessed by upper layers to achieve the desired level of security.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Higher-layer processes may specify keys to perform symmetric cryptography to protect the payload and restrict it to a group of devices or just a point-to-point link; these groups of devices can be specified in access control lists.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Furthermore, MAC computes *freshness checks* between successive receptions to ensure that presumably old frames, or data which is no longer considered valid, does not transcend to higher layers.
[src:thread-network-deep/ieee-802-15-4] In addition to this secure mode, there is another, insecure MAC mode, which allows access control lists merely as a means to decide on the acceptance of frames according to their (presumed) source.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:thread-network-deep/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] In July 2014, the Thread Group alliance was formed as an industry group to develop, maintain and drive adoption of Thread as an industry networking standard for IoT applications.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] Thread Group provides certification for components and products to ensure adherence to the spec.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] Initial members were ARM Holdings, Big Ass Solutions, NXP Semiconductors/Freescale, Google-subsidiary Nest Labs, OSRAM, Samsung, Silicon Labs, Somfy, Tyco International, Qualcomm, and the Yale lock company.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] In August 2018, Apple joined the group, and released its first Thread product, the HomePod Mini, in late 2020.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] The Thread protocol specification is available at no cost.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] Thread uses IPv6 over Low-Power Wireless Personal Area Networks (6LoWPAN), which, in turn, uses LR-WPAN as defined by the IEEE 802.15.4 wireless protocol with mesh communication (in the 2.4 GHz spectrum), as do Zigbee and other systems.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] However, Thread is IP-addressable, with cloud access and AES encryption.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] A BSD-licensed open-source implementation of Thread called *OpenThread* is available from and managed by Google.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] The OpenThread network simulator, a part of the OpenThread implementation, simulates Thread networks using OpenThread POSIX instances.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] The simulator utilises discrete-event simulation and allows for visualisation of communications through a web interface.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] A Thread border router is a device that provides bidirectional Internet Protocol connectivity between a Thread network and another physical network, such as Wi-Fi or Ethernet.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] It enables communication between Thread devices and other local networks or the Internet.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] A Thread network is a low-power mesh network using the IEEE 802.15.4 protocol in the 2.4 GHz ISM radio band, and a border router translates between such a network another physical network, allows for service discovery across network boundaries, and enables external commissioning of Thread devices.
[src:thread-network-deep/thread-network-protocol] Without a border router, Thread devices would be isolated from other networks and the Internet.
